{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"19a7e65b-bb3c-42a2-82a2-c1d5e77d7456","content":"A **NullReferenceException** is a runtime application error — it means your code is dereferencing a null object reference. This is **not** a CLR activation issue.\n\n**CLR activation logs** diagnose problems like:\n- Wrong .NET runtime version being loaded\n- Runtime failing to load at all\n- Unexpected Feature-on-Demand dialogs\n\nThey won't help find a `NullReferenceException` bug.\n\n**To diagnose your crash, I'd recommend:**\n1. Check the **stack trace** from the exception — it shows exactly which line has the null reference.\n2. Enable `--verbose` or attach a debugger to capture the full exception details.\n3. Share the stack trace or crash log here and I can help pinpoint the issue.\n\nDo you have a stack trace, crash dump, or source code you'd like me to look at?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bf8300a0-adab-4638-9656-3d86fac906a2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs for a .NET app crash. Let me check if there's a relevant skill for this.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see \"clr-activation-debugging\" which is described as: \"Diagnoses .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs (CLRLoad logs) produced by mscoree.dll.\"\n\nHowever, the user's issue is a NullReferenceException, not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs help diagnose issues with the CLR shim picking the wrong runtime, failing to load a runtime, etc. A NullReferenceException is a runtime error in the application code, not a CLR activation problem.\n\n\nI should clarify this distinction for the user rather than applying a tool that won't address their actual problem.","outputTokens":387,"requestId":"D817:112B3A:3120406:360B9E7:69FBEC7B"},"id":"8e3edb2e-66d0-4293-a1ef-d76d5a3c2f51","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:36:06.744Z","parentId":"53dab802-2abb-4dc3-978e-a79956c4eff2"}
